## Test Data: Factories Over Static Fixtures

Static fixture objects have two failure modes: they contain fields irrelevant to the test (noise), and they break all at once when the type gains a required field.

Use typed factory functions with sensible defaults. Override only what is relevant to the test.

```typescript
// src/features/alerts/__fixtures__/makeAlert.ts
import type { Alert } from '../types'; // typed against the feature's own types — compile error if type drifts
import type { OrgId } from '@/types';
import { toAlertId, toOrgId } from '@/types';

// Use a closure counter — each call to makeAlertFactory() creates an isolated sequence.
// Import the factory, not the counter, to avoid shared mutable state across test files.
export const makeAlertFactory = () => {
  let seq = 0;
  return (overrides: Partial<Alert> = {}): Alert => ({
    id: toAlertId(`alert-${++seq}`),
    orgId: toOrgId('org-test') as OrgId,
    severity: 'medium',
    title: 'Test alert',
    status: 'active',
    issuedAt: '2020-01-01T00:00:00.000Z', // fixed past date — never relative to Date.now()
    ...overrides,
  });
};

// Each test file creates its own factory instance — no shared counter state
export const makeAlert = makeAlertFactory();
```

```typescript
// In each test file that needs stable sequential IDs:
import { makeAlertFactory } from '../__fixtures__/makeAlert';
const makeAlert = makeAlertFactory(); // fresh sequence starting at 0

// ✅ Test only what matters — everything else uses the default
it('shows the resolved state correctly', () => {
  render(<AlertCard {...makeAlert({ status: 'resolved' })} />);
  expect(screen.getByRole('status')).toHaveTextContent(/resolved/i);
});

// ❌ Irrelevant fields cluttering the test
render(<AlertCard id="alert-1" severity="medium" title="Test" status="resolved"
  issuedAt="2020-01-01T00:00:00.000Z" orgId="org-1" source="scanner" ... />);
```

