## Component Tests (Vitest + RTL)

**What belongs here:** UI states, user interactions, conditional rendering, accessibility.

**Performance target:** under 500ms per test file.

### Query priority — highest to lowest

Always use the highest-priority query available. Lower-priority queries couple tests to markup structure.

| Priority | Query | Use when |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `getByRole` | Any element with a semantic role — covers most cases |
| 2 | `getByLabelText` | Form inputs — the label is the user-visible name |
| 3 | `getByPlaceholderText` | Input without an associated label |
| 4 | `getByText` | Non-interactive content |
| 5 | `getByDisplayValue` | Current value of a select or input |
| 6 | `getByAltText` | Images |
| 7 | `getByTitle` | Last resort for tooltip/title attributes |
| 8 | `getByTestId` | Only for elements with no semantic role — container divs, canvas |

```typescript
// ✅
screen.getByRole('button', { name: /dismiss/i })
screen.getByRole('alert')
await screen.findByRole('list', { name: /active alerts/i })

// ❌ — first choice
screen.getByTestId('dismiss-button')
```

### Use `userEvent` — never `fireEvent`

`userEvent.setup()` simulates the full browser event chain (pointerdown, focus, input, keydown, change, blur). `fireEvent` dispatches one synthetic event — it bypasses focus management, validation, and keyboard handlers.

```typescript
// ✅
it('calls onDismiss when the dismiss button is clicked', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  const onDismiss = vi.fn();
  render(<AlertCard {...makeAlert()} onDismiss={onDismiss} />);

  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /dismiss/i }));

  expect(onDismiss).toHaveBeenCalledExactlyOnceWith(alert.id); // called with the branded AlertId
});

// ❌
fireEvent.click(screen.getByTestId('dismiss-btn'));
```

### Test the four render states — only for components that own data fetching

Components that call a data-fetching hook directly have four states to test. **Presentational components that receive status as a prop do not** — testing `<AlertCard status="loading" />` is testing a prop, not behavior.

```typescript
// AlertList.test.tsx — AlertList calls useAlerts() internally
describe('AlertList', () => {
  it('shows a skeleton while fetching', async () => {
    server.use(http.get('/api/alerts', () => HttpResponse.json(mockAlerts, { delay: Infinity })));
    render(<AlertList />);
    expect(screen.getByRole('status', { name: /loading/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  it('shows an error state when the request fails', async () => {
    server.use(http.get('/api/alerts', () => HttpResponse.error()));
    render(<AlertList />);
    await screen.findByRole('alert', { name: /could not load/i });
  });

  it('shows an empty state when no alerts are returned', async () => {
    server.use(http.get('/api/alerts', () => HttpResponse.json([])));
    render(<AlertList />);
    await screen.findByText(/no active alerts/i);
  });

  it('renders a row for each alert', async () => {
    server.use(http.get('/api/alerts', () => HttpResponse.json([makeAlert(), makeAlert()])));
    render(<AlertList />);
    expect(await screen.findAllByRole('listitem')).toHaveLength(2);
  });
});
```

Note: use `HttpResponse.json(..., { delay: Infinity })` from MSW for the loading state — not a never-resolving `new Promise(() => {})`, which leaks across tests.

### Never assert on implementation details

```typescript
// ❌ Breaks on CSS rename — not a behavior change
expect(badge).toHaveClass('badge--critical');

// ❌ Breaks on state management change — not a behavior change
expect(component.state.isDismissed).toBe(true);

// ✅ Observable to the user — survives any internal refactor
expect(screen.queryByText('Exposed API key')).not.toBeInTheDocument();
```

