## End-to-End Tests (Playwright)

**What belongs here:** critical user journeys only. A critical journey is one where a failure prevents the user from achieving the core purpose of the application.

**Justify every E2E test:** before adding one, answer "why can an integration test not cover this?" Acceptable answers: requires a real network stack, tests authentication flows, verifies browser-specific behavior (file download, clipboard, print).

### Critical journeys for a security dashboard

- Authentication: login, session expiry redirect, logout
- Primary dashboard: loads and displays real data
- Alert escalation or dismissal end-to-end through real API
- Report export producing a valid file

### Page Object Model

Consider Page Objects when two or more E2E specs share the same selectors. Do not introduce them speculatively. At MVP, each of the four E2E specs covers a distinct user journey — POM is not required until selector duplication is observed.

When selectors are duplicated across two specs, extract them:

Selectors live in Page Objects. Test files contain only behavior and assertions.

```typescript
// e2e/pages/AlertsPage.ts
export class AlertsPage {
  constructor(private readonly page: Page) {}

  async goto() { await this.page.goto('/alerts'); }

  async waitForLoaded() {
    await expect(this.page.getByRole('list', { name: /alerts/i })).toBeVisible();
  }

  async dismissAlert(title: string) {
    await this.page
      .getByRole('button', { name: new RegExp(`dismiss ${title}`, 'i') })
      .click();
  }

  alertItem(title: string) {
    return this.page.getByRole('listitem').filter({ hasText: title });
  }
}

// e2e/alerts.spec.ts
test('dismissed alert is removed from the list', async ({ page }) => {
  const alertsPage = new AlertsPage(page);
  await alertsPage.goto();
  await alertsPage.waitForLoaded();

  await alertsPage.dismissAlert('Exposed API key');

  await expect(alertsPage.alertItem('Exposed API key')).not.toBeVisible();
});
```

### Never use fixed waits. Never poll with `page.waitForTimeout`.

```typescript
// ❌
await page.waitForTimeout(2000);

// ✅ Playwright auto-retries until the assertion passes or times out
await expect(page.getByRole('list', { name: /alerts/i })).toBeVisible();
```

### Flaky test policy

A flaky test is a broken test. Do not skip it, do not retry it, do not ignore it. Fix the root cause or delete the test. A suite with known flaky tests cannot be trusted.

