## Accessibility Testing

### Axe at the integration layer, per render state

Run axe at the integration test level where the full component tree is mounted. Do not run axe on every individual component in isolation — the coverage gain is marginal and the duplication is high. Target states that the default render won't hit: error state, empty state, modal open.

```typescript
import { axe } from 'vitest-axe';

it('has no accessibility violations in the populated state', async () => {
  render(<AlertsFeature />);
  await screen.findAllByRole('listitem');
  expect(await axe(document.body)).toHaveNoViolations();
});

it('has no accessibility violations in the error state', async () => {
  server.use(http.get('/api/alerts', () => HttpResponse.error()));
  render(<AlertsFeature />);
  await screen.findByRole('alert');
  expect(await axe(document.body)).toHaveNoViolations();
});
```

### Keyboard navigation — test interactive components explicitly

```typescript
it('dismiss button is keyboard accessible and activates on Enter', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  const onDismiss = vi.fn();
  render(<AlertCard {...makeAlert()} onDismiss={onDismiss} />);

  await user.tab();
  expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /dismiss/i })).toHaveFocus();

  await user.keyboard('{Enter}');
  expect(onDismiss).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
});
```

