## Mocking Strategy

### Network: MSW at the network layer

MSW intercepts at `fetch`/`XHR` level and is immune to import path changes.

```typescript
// ✅
server.use(http.get('/api/alerts', () => HttpResponse.json([makeAlert()])));

// ❌ Breaks when the file is renamed or moved
vi.mock('@/features/alerts/api', () => ({ getAlerts: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue([]) }));
```

### Module mocks: only for these specific cases

Use `vi.mock` only when MSW cannot intercept the dependency:

| Use `vi.mock` for | Do not use `vi.mock` for |
|---|---|
| `window.matchMedia` | API calls |
| `IntersectionObserver` | Feature modules |
| `localStorage` / `sessionStorage` | Utility functions you control |
| `navigator.clipboard` | React Query hooks |
| Third-party analytics SDKs (no fetch) | Any module with a fetch equivalent |

### Factories over static fixtures

See the Test Data section above. Factories are typed against feature types — when the type changes, the factory fails to compile, not silently at runtime.

### `vi.clearAllMocks()` runs after every test

This is enforced in `setupTests.ts`. You do not need to reset mocks manually in individual tests unless you need a specific call count from `beforeEach`.

